{"key":"processedPost-9391020","value":{"id":9391020,"first":9391002,"last":9393119,"when":1228753532,"utime":"12/08/08 06:25 PM","content":"I recommend around a teaspoon of hydrated lime per cup of peat.&nbsp; That will leave you around 8.5 for a day or two, when it settles down to around 7.5 or so.&nbsp; I suspect your pH meter isn't calibrated, especially if you used gypsum at ten percent of the volume of peat.<br /><br />You might try repeating the test after calibrating your meter in pH 7 solution.&nbsp; Be sure to filter the material back out of the water and test only water, especially if you are using a bulb type pH meter.<br /><br />You might also check your label against the picture below.&nbsp; When using hydrated lime, it's important to use <i>horticultura</i>l hydrated lime, not the type intended for masonry.<br />RR<br /><a href=\"https://files.shroomery.org/files/06-29/352394956-hydrated_lime_label.jpg\" class=\"highslide\" onclick=\"return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})\" target=\"_blank\"><img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"/forums/thumbs/06-29/352394956-thumb_hydrated_lime_label.jpg\"></a> <a href=\"https://files.shroomery.org/files/032303-8/89949-lime1.jpg\" class=\"highslide\" onclick=\"return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})\" target=\"_blank\"><img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"/forums/thumbs/032303-8/89949-thumb_lime1.jpg\"></a>","title":"Re: 50/50+ casing questions (RR's recipe) - 9.5 pH?!"}}